ref: Jour: Physical Review, Vol.175, Issue.4, p.1330 (1968)
title: Fast-Photoneutron Spectra Due To 55-85-Mev Photons.

x4codes.hlp: Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Troy, NY, United States of America

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physical Review, Vol.175, Issue.4, p.1330 (1968)

x4codes.hlp: Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, Troy, NY, United States of America

x4freetext: SOLID SAMPLES  WERE CIRCULAR DISKS OF 3/4 IN. OR 1 IN.
DIAMETER ORIENTED SO THAT THE DISK AXIS COINCIDED WITH
THE PHOTON BEAM AXIS. DISK THICKNESSES WERE 1/8 IN. OR
3/16 IN. FOR HEAVIER NUCLEI (Z>20) AND BETWEEN 1 AND 2
IN. FOR LIGHTER ELEMENTS. WATER AND LIQUID NITROGEN IN
THIN-WALLED ALUMINIUM CONTAINERS WERE USED AS THE SAM-
PLES FOR THE STUDIES OF OXYGEN AND NITROGEN.
. FLIGHT PATH = 100 M, TIME RESOLUTION = 0.4 NS/M
.LIQUID SCINTILLATOR TANK OF 5 IN. IN THICKNESS
AND 20 IN. IN DIAMETER VIEWED  BY SEVEN PHILIPS 58 AVP
THE NEUTRON SPECTRA OBTAINED AT BREMSSTRAHLUNG END-PO-
INT ENERGIES OF 55 AND 85 MEV WERE NORMALIZED FOR EQU-
AL NUMBERS OF PHOTONS AT THE GIANT-RESONANCE PEAK ENE-
RGY. THE NEUTRON DIFFERENCE SPECTRUM WAS CALCULATED BY
MEANS  OF SUBTRACTION  OF 55-MEV NEUTRON SPECTRUM FROM
85 MEV NEUTRON SPECTRUM.THE PHOTON DIFFERENCE SPECTRUM
WAS CALCULATED  AS THE DIFFERENCE BETWEEN  85- AND 55-
MEV BREMSSTRAHLUNG SPECTRA. THE EFFECTIVE DOUBLE DIFF-
ERENTIAL  CROSS  SECTION  WAS OBTAINED BY DIVIDING THE
NEUTRON DIFFERENCE SPECTRUM  BY  THE PHOTON DIFFERENCE
ENERGY SPECTRA WERE CORRECTED FOR (A) THE PHOTON ATTE-
NUATION IN THE SAMPLES , (B) THE SCATTERING OF THE OU-
TGOING NEUTRONS IN THE SAMPLES , (C) THE DETECTOR EFF-
ENERGY SPECTRA OF FAST PHOTONEUTRONS FROM EIGHTEEN EL-
EMENTS WERE MEASURED. MEASUREMENTS OF THE SPECTRA FROM
EACH TARGET  AT BREMSSTRAHLUNG ENERGIES OF BOTH 55 AND
85 MEV PERMITTED EXTRACTION OF NEUTRON DIFFERENCE SPE-
CTRA EFFICTIVELY DUE TO PHOTONS BETWEEN 55 AND 85 MEV.
DIFFERENCE SPECTRA  WERE OBTAINED FOR NEUTRON ENERGIES
GREATER THAN 10 MEV. THE EXPERIMENTAL DATA WERE COMPA-
RED TO THE PREDICTIONS OF THE QUASIDEUTERON MODEL WITH
SECONDARY-NEUTRON EFFECTS ESTIMATED BY MONTE CARLO CA-
LCULATIONS.GOOD AGREEMENT WAS OBTAINED FOR THE ABSOLU-
TE-NEUTRON-PRODUCTION CROSS SECTIONS AND THE SHAPES OF
THE NEUTRON ENERGY SPECTRA  OVER  THE RANGE OF TARGETS
.COMPILED IN SCJAD OF SARATOV STATE UNIVERSITY
